<br>
I think most people missed the question.  Simply put the most complex classes are the answer.  It's more complicated than that though, as it really depends on your play style.  For me, skill is a very important aspect of the game.  <br>
<br>
Alot of people will say skill has little to do with the game.  That's because they've systematically done everything in their power to do away with skill when they play.  They level up in LoIO, OT, DL, VL because it's the fastest way to level.  It's easier because there's reduced risk, which means less skill is required.  They AA in FG, because they know they won't die.  On raids they approach every encounter with a formula.  We need X number of such-and-such class (for example, cleric) in order to have almost zero chance of failure, so we'll wait until we have the people to fit the formula.  If you play the game this way, skill means almost nothing.  Everything is boiled down to level, class, gear and just about any person can fill another's shoes.<br>
<br>
If you take the opposite approach and try to find the most challenging spots to experience in.  If you seek out the places to experience in where you're most likely to die at least once or twice a night.  If, when you raid, you know you'll succeed with X number of clerics, so next time you try with X-1.  If you're an envelope pusher, then skill matters the most.  Level, class, gear become less important, as you find you can get around class requirements, but you cannot abide an unskilled player.<br>
<br>
If you're a member of the second, (much) smaller group of people then any class you play will be tough to play well.<br>
<br>
Muse Ryenia Skylark<br>
