<br>
Then again, 52nd is my level, so who am I to say? I've been Raid Slow on Chardok raids a 5-6 times over the years, and have done it, as ordered, in pref to higher level shammies that were known to be crap-ola. <br>
<br>
Still, for a person who is already good player, shaman is an easy class to pick up and learn. <br>
<br>
I actually see about three different threads here. <br>
<br>
1) What is the hardest class to play?<br>
2) What is the easiest class to play?<br>
3) Does player skill even matter?<br>
<br>
I say player skill matters greatly. I will say that I think it matters less now than it did 2 years ago. Witness those times when the hard-core bad-asses of your guild had to attempt that Fear break-in nekkid using only the crap stuff they had stored in the bank because your whole raid was dead in Fear. That they succeeded means they were pretty damned skilled. <br>
<br>
Watch that monk what comes out of retirement after a year, dressed in half a kit (the no drop stuff he couldn't give away), split zeks in Kael on his first day back.<br>
<br>
Is it a big deal? Not overly, but it shows that skill can mean something when you strip away uber gear. Mudflation is part of the problem here. The cheesy gear my 37th lev halfling warrior has today would've made the 50's pre-Kunark absolutely faint dead away. That gear makes things ever so much more easy and allows for slackers to still perform well sans skill.<br>
